{"title_page": "Wax gourd", "text_new": "{{Redirect2|Kundol|Benincasa|the lake|Kundol Lake|the surname Benincasa|Benincasa (surname)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{primary sources|date=January 2018}}\n{{Copy edit|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{stack begin}}\n{{speciesbox\n|name = Wax gourd, Significant Melon\n|image = Benincasa hispida compose.jpg\n|image_caption = Wax gourd plant, flower, immature and mature fruit\n|display_parents = 3\n|genus = Benincasa\n|parent_authority = [[Gaetano Savi|Savi]]\n|species = hispida\n|authority = ([[Carl Peter Thunberg|Thunb.]]) Cogn.\n|synonyms =\n  {{Collapsible list |\n    {{Plainlist | style = margin-left: 1em; text-indent: -1em; |\n* ''Benincasa cerifera'' <small>Savi</small>\n* ''Benincasa cylindrica'' <small>Ser.</small> nom. inval.\n* ''Benincasa pruriens'' <small>(Parkinson) W.J.de Wilde & Duyfjes</small> nom. inval.\n* ''Benincasa vacua'' <small>(F.Muell.) F.Muell.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita alba'' <small>Roxb. ex Wight & Arn.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita farinosa'' <small>Blume</small>\n* ''Cucurbita hispida'' <small>Thunb.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita littoralis'' <small>Hassk.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita pruriens'' <small>Parkinson</small> nom. inval.\n* ''Cucurbita pruriens'' <small>Seem.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita vacua'' <small>F.Muell.</small>\n* ''Cucurbita villosa'' <small>Blume</small>\n* ''Gymnopetalum septemlobum'' <small>Miq.</small>\n    }}\n  }}\n|synonyms_ref = <ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.theplantlist.org/tpl1.1/record/kew-2673135\n|title=The Plant List: A Working List of All Plant Species\n|accessdate=April 10, 2014}}</ref>\n|}}\n{{stack end}}\n{{nutritional value | name= Waxgourd, raw\n| kJ=54\n| protein=0.4 g\n| fat=0.2 g\n| carbs=3 g\n| fiber=2.9 g\n| calcium_mg=19\n| iron_mg=0.4\n| magnesium_mg=10\n| phosphorus_mg=19\n| sodium_mg=111\n| zinc_mg=0.61\n| manganese_mg=0.058\n| vitC_mg=13\n| thiamin_mg=0.04\n| riboflavin_mg=0.11\n| niacin_mg=0.4\n| pantothenic_mg=0.133\n| vitB6_mg=0.035\n| source_usda = 1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=11593&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\n'''''Benincasa hispida''''', the '''wax gourd''',<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/plant/wax-gourd Wax Gourd], Editors of 'Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'. Accessed on 19.11.2012.</ref><ref>Useful Tropical Plants, '[http://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=Benincasa+hispida Benincasa hispida]'. Accessed on 19.11.2017.</ref> also called '''ash gourd''',<ref name=MMPND/> '''white gourd''', '''winter gourd''', '''tallow gourd''', '''ash pumpkin''', '''winter melon''',<ref name=MMPND>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantnames.unimelb.edu.au/Sorting/Benincasa.html |title=Multilingual Multiscript Plant Name Database |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> '''Chinese preserving melon'''<ref name=MMPND/> and '''(Alu) Puhul''', is a [[vine]] grown for its very large [[fruit]], eaten as a [[vegetable]] when mature.\n\nIt is the only member of the genus '''''Benincasa'''''. The fruit is covered in a fuzzy coating of fine hairs when young. The immature melon has thick white flesh that tastes sweet. By maturity, the fruit loses its hairs and develops a [[wax]]y coating, giving rise to the name ''wax gourd''. The wax coating helps to give the fruit a long [[shelf life]]. The melon may grow as large as 80&nbsp;cm in length. \nIt has yellow flowers and broad leaves.<ref name=handbook>D. K. Salunkhe and S. S. Kadam (Editors){{google books|Ns4vQyf-zI0C|Handbook of Vegetable Science and Technology: Production, Composition, Storage and Processing|page=290}}</ref> The taste is rather bland.<ref>Specialty Produce, '[http://www.specialtyproduce.com/produce/Winter_Melon_7661.php Winter Melon]'. Accessed on 19.11.2017.</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\nIt is native to [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. The wax gourd is widely grown throughout [[Asia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/PlantFinder/PlantFinderDetails.aspx?kempercode=e457|title=Benincasa hispida - Plant Finder|website=www.missouribotanicalgarden.org}}</ref> including [[Java]] and [[Japan]],<ref name=Crops>T. R. Gopalakrishnan {{google books|-mTUBjSyo_UC|Vegetable Crops|page=138}}</ref> the places where it is thought to have originated and [[Sri Lanka]].<ref name=handbook/>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name \u201cwinter melon\u201d that is sometimes given to this plant is based on the Chinese name {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|d\u014dnggu\u0101}} ({{lang|zh|\u51ac\u74dc}}); however, the [[Chinese character|character]] {{lang|zh|\u74dc}} ({{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|gu\u0101}}) can also mean \u201cgourd\u201d or \u201csquash.\u201d<ref>[https://www.mdbg.net/chinese/dictionary?page=worddict&wdrst=0&wdqb=%E5%86%AC%E7%93%9C%E7%B3%96 MDBG Word Dictionary]</ref> It is likely that the name \u201cmelon\u201d is given because this gourd is sometimes candied or made into a sweet tea; see the [[#Uses|Uses]] section below.\n\n==Cultivation==\nIt is grown in well-drained [[loam]] and sandy soils, in warm mild climates, but will not tolerate frosts. The crops are grown in riverbeds or [[furrows]], and needs constant [[irrigation]] during the growing season.<ref name=handbook/>\n\n==Uses==\nThe wax gourd requires very warm weather to grow but can be stored for many months much like [[winter squash]]. Ash gourds of the Indian subcontinent have a white coating with rough texture (hence the name ash gourd). South East Asian varieties have a smooth waxy texture. It is one of the few vegetables available during winter in areas of [[deciduous]] [[vegetation]]. Its Chinese name literally means 'winter gourd.' Wax gourds can typically be stored for 12 months. In India, the wax gourd is recognized for its medicinal properties in the [[Ayurveda|Ayurvedic system of medicine]].<ref name=Crops/> It is also has significance in spiritual traditions of [[India]] and [[Yoga]], where it is identified as a great source of [[Prana]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://isha.sadhguru.org/blog/lifestyle/food/ash-gourd-winter-melon-cool-vegetable-benefits-recipes/|title=Ash Gourd (Winter Melon), the \"Cool\" Vegetable: Benefits & Recipes - The Isha Blog|date=2017-05-04|work=The Isha Blog|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn [[Vietnamese cuisine]], it is called ''b\u00ed \u0111ao'', which is usually used to make soup or stew.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winter Melon Soup - Canh B\u00ed \u0110ao|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm3nzo3OCtg|date=30 August 2014|publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> When cooked with pork short ribs, the resulting soup is traditionally thought to help produce more milk for breastfeeding mothers.{{Citation needed|reason=reliable source needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn Chinese cuisine, the gourds are used in stir fries or usually combined with pork or pork/beef bones to make winter gourd soup, often served in the scooped out gourd, carved by scraping off the waxy coating. It is also chopped and [[candied]]<ref>{{cite web|title=How to make Candied Winter Melon aka Tung Kua(\u51ac\u74dc\u7cd6)|url=http://unclephilipsg.blogspot.com/2009/05/how-to-make-candied-winter-melon-aka.html|accessdate=18 December 2011|year=2009}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}} as [[Chinese candy box|wintermelon candy]] (t\u00e1ng d\u014dng gu\u0101) to be commonly eaten at [[Chinese New Year|New Year festivals]], or as filling for [[Sweetheart cake]] (l\u01ceop\u00f3 b\u01d0ng). It has also been used as the base filling in Chinese and Taiwanese [[mooncake]]s for the Moon Festival.\n\nIn the [[Philippines]] it is candied (referred to plainly as ''kundol'') and is used as a pastry filling for [[bakpia]] (''hopia'' in the Philippines).  It is also an ingredient in some savory soups (sabaw) and stir-fries (guisado).\n\nIn Indian cuisine this gourd is traditionally used to prepare a wide variety of dishes. In northern India it is used to prepare a candy called ''[[petha]]''. In [[South Indian cuisine]], it is traditionally used to make a variety of [[Curry|curries]], including a stew made with a [[yogurt]] base.<ref name=\"Majjige Huli\">{{cite web|title=Majjige huli with winter melon|url=http://www.paajaka.com/2008/02/majjige-huli-with-winter-melon.html}}</ref> The juice of raw ash gourd (Maipawl) or (Khar) is used by the [[Mizo people|Mizo community]] and [[Assamese people|indigenous Assamese ethnicities]] of North-East India as a natural remedy to treat mild to severe dysentery. In north India, particularly in middle Himalayas, it is paired with pulses such as [[Mung bean|moong]] which when crushed, along with winter gourd, results in the making of a dish locally called ''bari''. When dried in sunlight it becomes somewhat hard and is used as a curry dish and eaten along with rice or [[chapati]]. This practice is done in [[Himalayas]] to help the mountain people survive harsh winters. This bari is a source of iron and vitamins{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}.\n\nIn [[Andhra Pradesh]], it is called \"boodidi gummidikaya\" ([[Telugu language]]). It is used to make stews, stir fries and vadialu. Vadialu (plural; vadiam is singular) are made by chopping the gourd in small pieces and mixing with yogurt and spices, then sun-drying. To eat, vadiams are deep fried in oil and eaten as an accompaniment to rice and [[sambar (dish)]] or lentil stews.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn [[Kerala]], the plant is called Kumbalam (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d33\u0d02) and the fruit is called Kumbalanga (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d33\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19) or Kooshmandam (\u0d15\u0d42\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d02). It is traditionally used to offer 'Guruthi' (\u0d17\u0d41\u0d30\u0d41\u0d24\u0d3f) instead of 'Kuruti' (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d30\u0d41\u0d24\u0d3f) among Malayali Brahmins. It means, instead of offering someone's life in the pier, an ash gourd is cut into two as a symbolic performance in lieu human sacrifice.\n\nIn [[Udupi cuisine]] , Ash gourd known as Budu Kumbda or Boldu Kumbda in [[Tulu language|Tulu]] language, Budi Kumblakayi in Kannada is used to prepare many dishes like Kodel([[Sambar (dish)|Sambhar]]),Ale bajji, Kashi Halwa and Chutney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://udupi-recipes.com/2017/11/ashgourd-kootu-recipe.html|title=Ashgourd Kootu Recipe Simple and easy|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn the [[Gujarat]], is called kolu (\u0a95\u0acb\u0ab3\u0ac1).\n\nIn [[Nepal]], where it is called Kubhindo, it is cooked as a vegetable when young, but the ripe gourds are usually made into preserves or crystallized candy known as \"murabba\" or \"petha\".<ref>Taste of Nepal, '[http://tasteofnepal.blogspot.com/2012/03/kubhindo-ash-gourd.html Kubhindo - Ash Gourd (\u0915\u0941\u092d\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0921\u094b)]'. Accessed 19.11.2017.</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\nOccasionally, it is used to produce a [[juice|fruit drink]] with a very distinctive taste. It is usually sweetened with caramelized sugar. In Southeast Asia, the drink is widely marketed as wax gourd tea or [[Winter melon punch|wax gourd punch]].\n\nThe [[shoot]]s, [[tendril]]s, and [[leaf|leaves]] of the plant may also be eaten as [[leaf vegetable|greens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=~Winter Squash Leaves in Salted Coconut Milk|url=https://praneesthaikitchen.com/2011/08/09/winter-squash-leaves-salted-coconut-milk/|date=9 August 2011|publisher=praneesthaikitchen.com|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:India Ash Gourd.jpg|Indian Ash Gourd\nFile:W tougan4091.jpg|Nearly mature wax gourd\nFile:Winter melon.jpg|Wax gourd\nFile:Winter melon seed.jpg|Seeds\nFile:Winter Melons on the vine in Kurnool, Andhra Pradesh, India 02.jpg|Wax gourd on the vine\nFile:Wintermelonsoup.jpg|Chinese winter [[melon soup]]\nFile:\u51ac\u74dc\u7cd6.jpg|Chinese winter melon candy\nFile:Winteelon flowers.jpg|Wax Gourd Plant flowering\nFile:Winter melon in backyard.jpg|Wax Gourd - 2 weeks since flowering\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n=