ourd, raw\n| kJ=54\n| protein=0.4 g\n| fat=0.2 g\n| carbs=3 g\n| fiber=2.9 g\n| calcium_mg=19\n| iron_mg=0.4\n| magnesium_mg=10\n| phosphorus_mg=19\n| sodium_mg=111\n| zinc_mg=0.61\n| manganese_mg=0.058\n| vitC_mg=13\n| thiamin_mg=0.04\n| riboflavin_mg=0.11\n| niacin_mg=0.4\n| pantothenic_mg=0.133\n| vitB6_mg=0.035\n| source_usda = 1\n| note=[http://ndb.nal.usda.gov/ndb/search/list?qlookup=11593&format=Full Link to USDA Database entry]\n}}\n\n'''''Benincasa hispida''''', the '''wax gourd''',<ref>[https://www.britannica.com/plant/wax-gourd Wax Gourd], Editors of 'Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica'. Accessed on 19.11.2012.</ref><ref>Useful Tropical Plants, '[http://tropical.theferns.info/viewtropical.php?id=Benincasa+hispida Benincasa hispida]'. Accessed on 19.11.2017.</ref> also called '''ash gourd''',<ref name=MMPND/> '''white gourd''', '''winter gourd''', '''tallow gourd''', '''ash pumpkin''', '''winter melon''',<ref name=MMPND>{{cite web |url=http://www.plantnames.unimelb.edu.au/Sorting/Benincasa.html |title=Multilingual Multiscript Plant Name Database |accessdate=10 April 2014}}</ref> '''Chinese preserving melon'''<ref name=MMPND/> and '''(Alu) Puhul''', is a [[vine]] grown for its very large [[fruit]], eaten as a [[vegetable]] when mature.\n\nIt is the only member of the genus '''''Benincasa'''''. The fruit is covered in a fuzzy coating of fine hairs when young. The immature melon has thick white flesh that is sweet when eaten. By maturity, the fruit loses its hairs and develops a [[wax]]y coating, giving rise to the name ''wax gourd''. The wax coating helps to give the fruit a long [[shelf life]]. The melon may grow as large as 80&nbsp;cm in length. \nIt has yellow flowers and broad leaves.<ref name=handbook>D. K. Salunkhe and S. S. Kadam (Editors){{google books|Ns4vQyf-zI0C|Handbook of Vegetable Science and Technology: Production, Composition, Storage and Processing|page=290}}</ref> The taste is rather bland.<ref>Specialty Produce, '[http://www.specialtyproduce.com/produce/Winter_Melon_7661.php Winter Melon]'. Accessed on 19.11.2017.</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\nIt is native to [[South Asia]] and [[Southeast Asia]]. The wax gourd is widely grown throughout Asia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.missouribotanicalgarden.org/PlantFinder/PlantFinderDetails.aspx?kempercode=e457|title=Benincasa hispida - Plant Finder|website=www.missouribotanicalgarden.org}}</ref> including [[Java]] and Japan,<ref name=Crops>T. R. Gopalakrishnan {{google books|-mTUBjSyo_UC|Vegetable Crops|page=138}}</ref> the places where it is thought to have originated and Sri Lanka.<ref name=handbook/>\n\n==Etymology==\nThe name \u201cwinter melon\u201d that is sometimes given to this plant is based on the Chinese name {{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|d\u014dnggu\u0101}} ({{lang|zh|\u51ac\u74dc}}); however, the [[Chinese character|character]] {{lang|zh|\u74dc}} ({{lang|zh-latn-pinyin|gu\u0101}}) can also mean \u201cgourd\u201d or \u201csquash\u201d.<ref>[https://www.mdbg.net/chinese/dictionary?page=worddict&wdrst=0&wdqb=%E5%86%AC%E7%93%9C%E7%B3%96 MDBG Word Dictionary]</ref> It is likely that the name \u201cmelon\u201d is given because this gourd is sometimes candied or made into a sweet tea; see the [[#Uses|Uses]] section below.\n\n==Cultivation==\nIt is grown in well-drained loam and sandy soils, in warm mild climates, but will not tolerate frosts. The crops are grown in riverbeds or [[furrows]], and needs constant irrigation during the growing season.<ref name=handbook/>\n\n==Uses==\nThe wax gourd requires very warm weather to grow but can be stored for many months much like [[winter squash]]. Ash gourds of the Indian subcontinent have a white coating with rough texture (hence the name ash gourd, literally, in some vernaculars). South East Asian varieties have a smooth waxy texture. It is one of the few vegetables available during winter in areas of [[deciduous]] [[vegetation]], hence its Chinese name literally means 'winter gourd'. Wax gourds can typically be stored for 12 months. In India, the wax gourd is recognized for its medicinal properties in the Ayurvedic system of medicine.<ref name=Crops/> It is also has significance in spiritual traditions of India and Yoga, where it is identified as a great source of [[Prana]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://isha.sadhguru.org/blog/lifestyle/food/ash-gourd-winter-melon-cool-vegetable-benefits-recipes/|title=Ash Gourd (Winter Melon), the \"Cool\" Vegetable: Benefits & Recipes - The Isha Blog|date=2017-05-04|work=The Isha Blog|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn Vietnamese cuisine, it is called ''b\u00ed \u0111ao'', which is usually used to make soup or stew.<ref>{{cite web|title=Winter Melon Soup - Canh B\u00ed \u0110ao|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Tm3nzo3OCtg|date=30 August 2014|publisher=youtube.com|accessdate=1 June 2017}}</ref> When cooked with pork short ribs, the resulting soup is traditionally thought to help produce more milk for breastfeeding mothers.{{Citation needed|reason=reliable source needed|date=August 2013}}\n\nIn Chinese cuisine the gourds are used in stir fries or usually combined with pork or pork/beef bones to make winter [[gourd soup]], often served in the scooped out gourd, carved by scraping off the waxy coating. It is also chopped and [[candied]]<ref>{{cite web|title=How to make Candied Winter Melon aka Tung Kua(\u51ac\u74dc\u7cd6)|url=http://unclephilipsg.blogspot.com/2009/05/how-to-make-candied-winter-melon-aka.html|accessdate=18 December 2011|year=2009}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}} as [[Chinese candy box|wintermelon candy]] (t\u00e1ng d\u014dng gu\u0101) to be commonly eaten at [[Chinese New Year|New Year festivals]], or as filling for [[Sweetheart cake]] (l\u01ceop\u00f3 b\u01d0ng). It has also been used as the base filling in Chinese and Taiwanese [[mooncake]]s for the Moon Festival.\n\nIn the Philippines it is candied (referred to plainly as ''kundol'') and is used as a pastry filling for [[bakpia]] (''hopia'' in the Philippines).  It is also an ingredient in some savory soups (sabaw) and stir-fries (guisado).\n\nIn Indian cuisine this gourd is traditionally used to prepare a wide variety of dishes. In northern India it is used to prepare a candy called ''[[petha]]''. In [[South Indian cuisine]], it is traditionally used to make a variety of curries, including a stew made with a yogurt base.<ref name=\"Majjige Huli\">{{cite web|title=Majjige huli with winter melon|url=http://www.paajaka.com/2008/02/majjige-huli-with-winter-melon.html}}</ref> The juice of raw ash gourd (Maipawl) or (Khar) is used by the [[Mizo people|Mizo community]] and [[Assamese people|indigenous Assamese ethnicities]] of North-East India as a natural remedy to treat mild to severe dysentery. In north India, particularly in middle Himalayas, it is paired with pulses such as moong which when squashed along with winter gourd results in the making of a dish locally called ''bari''. When dried in the cool winter sunlight it becomes somewhat hard and is used as a curry dish and eaten along with rice or chapati. This practice is done in Himalayas for quite a long time as people in mountains depend upon nature to help them survive harsh winters. This bari is a great source of iron and vitamins and eaten diversely in the mountains.\n\nIn [[Andhra Pradesh]], it is called \"boodidi gummidikaya\" ([[Telugu language]]). It is used to make stews, stir fries and vadialu. Vadialu (plural; vadiam is singular) are made by chopping the gourd in small pieces and mixing with yogurt and spices, then sun-drying. To eat, vadiams are deep fried in oil and eaten as an accompaniment to rice and [[sambar (dish)]] or lentil stews.\n\nIn [[Kerala]], the plant is called Kumbalam (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d33\u0d02) and the fruit is called Kumbalanga (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d33\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19) or Kooshmandam (\u0d15\u0d42\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d02). It is traditionally used to offer 'Guruthi' (\u0d17\u0d41\u0d30\u0d41\u0d24\u0d3f) instead of 'Kuruti' (\u0d15\u0d41\u0d30\u0d41\u0d24\u0d3f) among Malayali Brahmins. It means, instead of offering someone's life in the pier, an ash gourd is cut into two as a symbolic performance in lieu human sacrifice.\n\nIn [[Udupi cuisine]] , Ash gourd known as Budu Kumbda or Boldu Kumbda in [[Tulu language|Tulu]] language, Budi Kumblakayi in Kannada is used to prepare many dishes like Kodel([[Sambar (dish)|Sambhar]]),Ale bajji, Kashi Halwa and Chutney.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://udupi-recipes.com/2017/11/ashgourd-kootu-recipe.html|title=Ashgourd Kootu Recipe Simple and easy|access-date=10 January 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn the [[Gujarat]], is called kolu (\u0a95\u0acb\u0ab3\u0ac1).\n\nIn Nepal, where it is called Kubhindo, it is cooked as a vegetable when young, but the ripe gourds are usually popular in making preserves or crystallized candied sweet known as \"murabba\" or \"petha\".<ref>Taste of Nepal, '[http://tasteofnepal.blogspot.com/2012/03/kubhindo-ash-gourd.html Kubhindo - Ash Gourd (\u0915\u0941\u092d\u093f\u0928\u094d\u0921\u094b)]'. Accessed 19.11.2017.</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\nOccasionally, it is used to produce a [[juice|fruit drink]] with a very distinctive taste. It is usually sweetened with caramelized sugar. In Southeast Asia, the drink is widely marketed as wax gourd tea or [[Winter melon punch|wax gourd punch]].\n\nThe [[shoot]]s, [[tendril]]s, and [[leaf|leaves]] of the plant may also be eaten as [[leaf vegetable|greens]].<ref>{{cite web|title=~Winter Squash Leaves in Salted Coconut Milk|url=https://praneesthaikitchen.com/2011/08/09/winter-squash-leaves-salted-coconut-milk/|date=9 August 2011|publisher=praneesthaikitchen.com|accessdate=2 June 2017}}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=January 2018}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:India Ash Gourd.jpg|Indian Ash Gourd\nFile:W tougan4091.jpg|Nearly mature wax gourd\nFile:Winter melon.jpg|Wax gourd\nFile:Winter melon seed.jpg|Seeds\nFile:Winter Melons on the vine in Kurnool, Andhra Pradesh, India 02.jpg|Wax gourd on the vine\nFile:Wintermelonsoup.jpg|Chinese winter [[melon soup]]\nFile:\u51ac\u74dc\u7cd6.jpg|Chinese winter melon candy\nFile:Winteelon flowers.jpg|Wax Gourd Plant flowering\nFile:Winter melon in backyard.jpg|Wax Gourd - 2 weeks since flowering\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commons category-inline|Benincasa hispida}}\n{{Melons}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q652206}}\n\n[[Category:Cucurbitoideae]]\n[[Category:Flora of Nepal]]\n[[Category:Fruit vegetables]]\n[[Category:Medicinal plants]]\n[[Category:Melons]]\n<!-- [[Category:Monotypic plant genera]] already in Benincasa redirect, which is the name of the genus-->\n[[Category:Philippine cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "AaronByers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor spelling, punctuation, and capitalization changes were made. Internal links were added, removed, and relocated per the Wikipedia style guide.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wax_gourd"}
{"title_page": "The Witch Tree Symbol", "text_new": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = The Witch Tree Symbol\n| image         = Ndtwtsbkcvr.jpg <!--prefer 1st edition-->\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Carolyn Keene]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series\t= [[Nancy Drew Mystery Stories]]\n| genre         = [[Juvenile literature]]\n| publisher     = [[Grosset & Dunlap]]\n| release_date  = 1955\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = \n| isbn          = 0-448-09532-7\n| congress= PZ7.K23 Nan no. 32 1974\n| oclc= 1083207\n| preceded_by   = [[The Scarlet Slipper Mystery]]\n| followed_by   = [[The Hidden Window Mystery]]\n}}\n\n\n'''''The Witch Tree Symbol''''' is the thirty-third volume in the [[Nancy Drew Mystery Stories]] series. It was first published in 1955 under the pseudonym [[Carolyn Keene]].<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/witch-tree-symbol/oclc/503166172 ''The Witch Tree Symbol''] at [[WorldCat]]</ref> The actual author was Stratemeyer Syndicate executive, [[Harriet Adams|Harriet Stratemeyer Adams]].\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{more plot|date=January 2015}}\nWhen a neighbor asks [[Nancy Drew]] to accompany her to an old uninhabited mansion, a new mystery opens up when they find that all the rare furniture is stolen and danger lurks on the second floor. Nancy finds a [[hex sign|witch tree symbol]] that leads her to [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] country in pursuit of a cunning and ruthless thief.\n\nThe friendly welcome the young detective and her friends Bess and [[George Fayne|George]] receive from the [[Amish]] people soon changes to hostility when it is rumored that Nancy is a witch! Superstition helps her adversary in his attempt to get her off his trail, but Nancy does not give up. She persistently uncovers one clue after another.\n\nNancy's intelligence and sleuthing ability finally lead to the solution of this puzzling case.\n\n==Adaptation ==\nThe 33th installment in the [[Nancy Drew]] [[point-and-click adventure game]] series by [[Her Interactive]], named ''[[Nancy Drew: Midnight in Salem]]'', is loosely based on the novel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nancy Drew}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature|Novels}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch Tree Symbol, The}}\n[[Category:Nancy Drew books]]\n[[Category:1955 American novels]]\n[[Category:1955 children's books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Amish in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Grosset & Dunlap books]]\n\n\n{{1950s-child-novel-stub}}\n{{1950s-ya-novel-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books -->\n| name          = The Witch Tree Symbol\n| image         = Ndtwtsbkcvr.jpg <!--prefer 1st edition-->\n| caption       = \n| author        = [[Carolyn Keene]]\n| country       = United States\n| language      = English\n| series\t= [[Nancy Drew Mystery Stories]]\n| genre         = [[Juvenile literature]]\n| publisher     = [[Grosset & Dunlap]]\n| release_date  = 1955\n| media_type    = Print (hardback & paperback)\n| pages         = \n| isbn          = 0-448-09532-7\n| congress= PZ7.K23 Nan no. 32 1974\n| oclc= 1083207\n| preceded_by   = [[The Scarlet Slipper Mystery]]\n| followed_by   = [[The Hidden Window Mystery]]\n}}\n\n\n'''''The Witch Tree Symbol''''' is the thirty-third volume in the [[Nancy Drew Mystery Stories]] series. It was first published in 1955 under the pseudonym [[Carolyn Keene]].<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/witch-tree-symbol/oclc/503166172 ''The Witch Tree Symbol''] at [[WorldCat]]</ref> The actual author was Stratemeyer Syndicate executive, [[Harriet Adams|Harriet Stratemeyer Adams]].\n\n==Plot summary==\n{{more plot|date=January 2015}}\nWhen a neighbor asks [[Nancy Drew]] to accompany her to an old uninhabited mansion, a new mystery opens up, and danger lurks on the second floor. Nancy finds a [[hex sign|witch tree symbol]] that leads her to [[Pennsylvania Dutch]] country in pursuit of a cunning and ruthless thief.\n\nThe friendly welcome the young detective and her friends Bess and [[George Fayne|George]] receive from the [[Amish]] people soon changes to hostility when it is rumored that Nancy is a witch! Superstition helps her adversary in his attempt to get her off his trail, but Nancy does not give up. She persistently uncovers one clue after another.\n\nNancy's intelligence and sleuthing ability finally lead to the solution of this puzzling case.\n\n==Adaptation ==\nThe 33th installment in the [[Nancy Drew]] [[point-and-click adventure game]] series by [[Her Interactive]], named ''[[Nancy Drew: Midnight in Salem]]'', is loosely based on the novel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Nancy Drew}}\n{{Portal |Children's literature|Novels}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Witch Tree Symbol, The}}\n[[Category:Nancy Drew books]]\n[[Category:1955 American novels]]\n[[Category:1955 children's books]]\n[[Category:Novels set in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Amish in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Grosset & Dunlap books]]\n\n\n{{1950s-child-novel-stub}}\n{{1950s-ya-novel-stub}}\n", "name_user": "68.98.54.244", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(just added some word the descrid it beeter)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Witch_Tree_Symbol"}
{"title_page": "Yang Hyang-ja", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{orphan|date=September 2019}}{{BLP sources|date=September 2019}}}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| office              = [[Ministry of Personnel Management|President of National Human Resource Management Institute]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1967|4|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Hwasun County]], [[South Jeolla Province]], [[South Korea]]\n| alma_mater          = now-Cyber University of Korea<br>[[Sungkyunkwan University]]\n| termstart           = 31 August 2018\n| termend             = 1 August 2019\n| president           = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n| primeminister       = [[Lee Nak-yeon]]\n| image               = Yang Hyang-ja.jpg\n| predecessor         = Oh Dong-ho\n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| termstart1          = 30 May 2020\n| constituency1       = [[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]] B\n| predecessor1        = [[Chun Jung-bae]]\n}}\n{{Korean name}}\n\n'''Yang Hyang-ja''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc591\ud5a5\uc790; [[Hanja]]:  \u6881\u9999\u5b50; born 4 April 1967) is a South Korean politician previously served as the 28th president of National Human Resource Management Institute (NHI) of [[Ministry of Personnel Management]] under President [[Moon Jae-in]]. She was the first woman to lead the Institute since the relevant position was founded in 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhi.go.kr/Introduce/introduce6/info1_3.htm|title=\uc5ed\ub300\uc6d0\uc7a5|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=ko|trans-title=List of President of the Institute|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from Gwangju Girls' Commercial High School, she went to [[Samsung Electronics]] at the age of 18 ([[East Asian age reckoning|or 19 in Korea]]) as an assistant to [[semiconductor memory]] researchers at the company. Since then she had worked for the company's departments related to memory semi-conductors for over three decades. In 2014 she was promoted to the executive for its flash memory development becoming its first female executive without higher education,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160301000383|title=[ELECTION 2016] Parties try to add diversity to election rosters|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2016-03-01|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref> from [[Honam]] region and one-year earlier than her co-workers.\n\nShe completed tertiary education while working at Samsung. She earned a bachelor degree from now-Cyber University of Korea, which was co-founded by Samsung in 2000, in 2005 and masters from [[Sungkyunkwan University]], which has close partnerships with Samsung, in 2008.\n\nShe was contacted by then-party leader [[Moon Jae-in]] in late 2015. She resigned from Samsung in December 2015 for her political career which began in 2016 when she officially became member of [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] and later nominee for [[Gwangju]] constituency at the 2016 general election. After losing her election, she continued her commitment to politics. She was one of five elected members of Supreme Council of party for two years before resigning for the president of the NHI in August 2018. \n\nIn 2020 general election, she defeated six-term parliamentarian [[Chun Jung-bae]] becoming the only woman representing a district in [[Honam]] region.  \n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!Year\n!District\n!Party Affiliation\n!Votes\n!Percentage of votes\n!Results\n|-\n|20th National Assembly General Election\n|2016\n|[[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]]  B\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|24,603\n|31.5%\n|Lost\n|-\n|21st National Assembly General Election\n|2020\n|[[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]]  B\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|61,279\n|75.83%\n|Won\n|}\n\n== Published works ==\nYang's biography, ''Fly Towards Dream Beyond Dream, Hyang-ja''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1077383238|title=Kkum neomeo kkum eul hyanghae nalja, Hyangja.|date=2018|publisher=Bitabeata|others=Yang, Hyangja., \uc591\ud5a5\uc790, 1967-|isbn=9791157061129|location=Seoul|oclc=1077383238}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Sungkyunkwan University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Gwangju]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Minjoo Party of Korea politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South Korean politician}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{orphan|date=September 2019}}{{BLP sources|date=September 2019}}}}\n\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| office              = [[Ministry of Personnel Management|President of National Human Resource Management Institute]]\n| party               = [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1967|4|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Hwasun County]], [[South Jeolla Province]], [[South Korea]]\n| alma_mater          = now-Cyber University of Korea<br>[[Sungkyunkwan University]]\n| termstart           = 31 August 2018\n| termend             = 1 August 2019\n| president           = [[Moon Jae-in]]\n| primeminister       = [[Lee Nak-yeon]]\n| image               = Yang Hyang-ja.jpg\n| predecessor         = Oh Dong-ho\n| office1             = Member of the [[National Assembly (South Korea)|National Assembly]]\n| termstart1          = 30 May 2020\n| constituency1       = [[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]] B\n| predecessor1        = [[Chun Jung-bae]]\n}}\n{{Korean name}}\n\n'''Yang Hyang-ja''' ([[Korean language|Korean]]: \uc591\ud5a5\uc790; [[Hanja]]:  \u6881\u9999\u5b50; born 4 April 1967) is a South Korean politician previously served as the 28th president of National Human Resource Management Institute (NHI) of [[Ministry of Personnel Management]] under President [[Moon Jae-in]]. She was the first woman to lead the Institute since the relevant position was founded in 1960s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nhi.go.kr/Introduce/introduce6/info1_3.htm|title=\uc5ed\ub300\uc6d0\uc7a5|last=|first=|date=|website=|language=ko|trans-title=List of President of the Institute|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nAfter graduating from Gwangju Girls' Commercial High School, she went to [[Samsung Electronics]] at the age of 18 ([[East Asian age reckoning|or 19 in Korea]]) as an assistant to [[semiconductor memory]] researchers at the company. Since then she had worked for the company's departments related to memory semi-conductors for over three decades. In 2014 she was promoted to the executive for its flash memory development becoming its first female executive without higher education,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20160301000383|title=[ELECTION 2016] Parties try to add diversity to election rosters|last=Herald|first=The Korea|date=2016-03-01|website=www.koreaherald.com|language=en|access-date=2019-08-25}}</ref> from [[Honam]] region and one-year earlier than her co-workers.\n\nShe completed tertiary education while working at Samsung. She earned a bachelor degree from now-Cyber University of Korea, which was co-founded by Samsung in 2000, in 2005 and masters from [[Sungkyunkwan University]], which has close partnerships with Samsung, in 2008.\n\nShe was contacted by then-party leader [[Moon Jae-in]] in late 2015. She resigned from Samsung in December 2015 for her political career which began in 2016 when she officially became member of [[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]] and later nominee for [[Gwangju]] constituency at the 2016 general election. After losing her election, she continued her commitment to politics. She was one of five elected members of Supreme Council of party for two years before resigning for the president of the NHI in August 2018. \n\nIn 2020 general election, she defeated six-term parliamentarian [[Chun Jung-bae]] becoming the only woman representing a district in [[Honam]] region.  \n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Election\n!Year\n!District\n!Party Affiliation\n!Votes\n!Percentage of votes\n!Results\n|-\n|20th National Assembly General Election\n|2016\n|[[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]]  B\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|24,603\n|31.5%\n|Lost\n|-\n|21st National Assembly General Election\n|2020\n|[[Gwangju]] [[Seo District, Gwangju|Seo]]  B\n|[[Democratic Party of Korea|Democratic Party]]\n|61,279\n|75.83%\n|Won\n|}\n\n== Published works ==\nYang's biography, ''Fly Towards Dream Beyond Dream, Hyang-ja''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/1077383238|title=Kkum neomeo kkum eul hyanghae nalja, Hyangja.|date=2018|publisher=Bitabeata|others=Yang, Hyangja., \uc591\ud5a5\uc790, 1967-|isbn=9791157061129|location=Seoul|oclc=1077383238}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Sungkyunkwan University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Gwangju]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Inter&anthro", "label": "safe", "comment": "says it in the article", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yang_Hyang-ja"}
{"title_page": "B\u00f8rge Monberg", "text_new": "'''B\u00f8rge Kj\u00e6r Monberg''' (August 24, 1905 &ndash; June 19, 1990) was a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[field hockey]] player who competed in the [[1928 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[J\u00e6gersborg]], [[Gentofte]] and died in [[Kalundborg]].\n\nIn 1928 he was a member of the Danish team which was eliminated in the first round of the [[Field hockey at the 1928 Summer Olympics|Olympic tournament]] after two wins and two losses. He played all four matches as back.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/borge-monberg-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monberg, Borge}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1928 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Kalundborg]]\n[[Category:People from Gentofte Municipality]]\n\n{{Denmark-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''B\u00f8rge Kj\u00e6r Monberg''' (August 24, 1905 &ndash; June 19, 1990) was a [[Denmark|Danish]] [[field hockey]] player who competed in the [[1928 Summer Olympics]].\n\nHe was born in [[J\u00e6gersborg]], [[Gentofte]] and died in [[Kalundborg]].\n\nIn 1928 he was a member of the Danish team which was eliminated in the first round of the [[Field hockey at the 1928 Summer Olympics|Olympic tournament]] after two wins and two losses. He played all four matches as back.\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/mo/borge-monberg-1.html profile]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monberg, Borge}}\n[[Category:1905 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Danish male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 1928 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Kalundborg]]\n{{Denmark-fieldhockey-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArbieP", "label": "safe", "comment": "addedCategory:Gentofte Municipality", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B%C3%B8rge_Monberg"}
{"title_page": "Gergely Krausz", "text_new": "{{Infobox badminton player\n| name                    = Gergely Krausz\n| image                   =\n| image_size              =\n| caption                 =\n| birth_name              =\n| birth_date              = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1993|12|25}}\n| birth_place             = [[M\u00f3r]], Hungary\n| residence               = hungary\n| height                  = 1.88 m\n| weight                  = 76 kg\n| country                 = {{HUN}}\n| years_active            =\n| handedness              =\n| coach                   =\n| event                   = Men's singles & doubles\n| highest_ranking         = 81 (MS 10 May 2018)<br/> 113 (MD 25 August 2016)<br/> 134 (XD 17 July 2014)\n| date_of_highest_ranking =\n| current_ranking         = 99\n| date_of_current_ranking = MS 25 February 2020\n| medal_templates         =\n| bwf_id                  = C21B8D34-FBF8-41E6-BE3C-49667A895A90\n}}\n\n'''Gergely Krausz''' (born 25 December 1993) is a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] badminton player.<ref>{{cite web|title=Players: Gergely Krausz |url=http://bwfbadminton.com/player/56755/gergely-krausz |website=bwfbadminton.com |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]]|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Gergely Krausz Full Profile |url=http://bwf.tournamentsoftware.com/profile/biography.aspx?id=C21B8D34-FBF8-41E6-BE3C-49667A895A90 |website=bwf.tournamentsoftware.com |publisher=[[Badminton World Federation]]|accessdate=28 October 2016}}</ref> in 2015, he was the winner mens double at the Turkey International\n21-6 21-6 ashkan fesahati-mohamadreza khanjani\n\n== Achievements ==\n\n=== BWF International Challenge/Series (2 titles, 3 runners-up) ===\n''Men's singles''\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"font-size: 90%;\"\n! Year\n! Tournament\n! Opponent\n! Score\n! Result\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#D5D5D5\"\n| align=\"center\" | 2020\n| align=\"left\" | [[Uganda International]]\n| align=\"left\" | {{flagicon|SRI}} 